{"title_page": "War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire", "text_new": "{{italictitle}}\n'''''War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire''''' is a 1935 non-fiction book by Tatsuji Takeuchi, published by [[Doubleday, Doran, and Company]].\n\nWilliam L. Langer of ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' described it as \"a scholarly and thoroughly documented analysis of the Japanese constitutional system and of the technique of Japanese diplomacy.\"<ref name=Langer>{{cite web|author=Langer, William L.|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/1936-04-01/war-and-diplomacy-japanese-empire|title=War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[Foreign Affairs]]|date=1936-04-01|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe author taught international relations at [[Kwansei Gakuin University]]. He wrote the body of his work in the [[University of Chicago]],<ref name=Spectator>{{cite web|author=Hudson, G|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/1st-may-1936/23/japan-and-the-world-war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japan|title=Japan and the World War and Diplomacy in the Japanese|work=[[Spectator]]|date=1936-05-01|volume=156|issue=5627|page=799|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref> which included the book in a series about war in the context of international relations. The author had access to multiple Japanese sources not yet available in the West.<ref name=Langer/> Most of the book was written in 1931, but publication was delayed after the [[Mukden Incident]]. The author wrote his preface at Kwansei Gakuin on June 20, 1935.<ref name=Spectator/>\n\n==Content==\nThe book covers the period up to 1933. The author did not intend to create a complete history of international relations between Japan and other countries. According to Takeuchi, \"the substance of policy\" is not the focus of the book, and instead \"procedure\" is the focus.<ref name=Spectator/>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Spectator]]'' stated that while Japan had not reached a \"totalitarian\" environment yet, in light of the increasing militarization, \"it seems strange that so independent a mind should be tolerated at all.\"<ref name=Spectator/> It argued in regards to the content about the [[invasion of Manchuria]] that it is \"a most valuable account\".<ref name=Spectator/>\n\nLanger praised the sourcing and described it as \"One of the most important books of the quarter.\"<ref name=Langer/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.6461 War And Diplomacy In The Japanese Empire]'' - [[Internet Archive]]\n* ''[https://www.questia.com/library/77350247/war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japanese-empire War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire]'' in [[Questia]]\n[[Category:1935 books]]\n{{book-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italictitle}}\n'''''War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire''''' is a 1935 non-fiction book by Tatsuji Takeuchi, published by [[Doubleday, Doran, and Company]].\n\nWilliam L. Langer of ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' described it as \"a scholarly and thoroughly documented analysis of the Japanese constitutional system and of the technique of Japanese diplomacy.\"<ref name=Langer>{{cite web|author=Langer, William L.|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/1936-04-01/war-and-diplomacy-japanese-empire|title=War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire|work=[[Foreign Affairs]]|date=1936-04-01|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe author taught international relations at [[Kwansei Gakuin University]]. He wrote the body of his work in the [[University of Chicago]],<ref name=Spectator>{{cite web|author=Hudson, G|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/1st-may-1936/23/japan-and-the-world-war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japan|title=Japan and the World War and Diplomacy in the Japanese|work=[[Spectator]]|date=1936-05-01|volume=156|issue=5627|page=799|accessdate=2020-04-24}}</ref> which included the book in a series about war in the context of international relations. The author had access to multiple Japanese sources not yet available in the West.<ref name=Langer/> Most of the book was written in 1931, but publication was delayed after the [[Mukden Incident]]. The author wrote his preface at Kwansei Gakuin on June 20, 1935.<ref name=Spectator/>\n\n==Content==\nThe book covers the period up to 1933. The author did not intend to create a complete history of international relations between Japan and other countries. According to Takeuchi, \"the substance of policy\" is not the focus of the book, and instead \"procedure\" is the focus.<ref name=Spectator/>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[The Spectator]]'' stated that while Japan had not reached a \"totalitarian\" environment yet, \"it seems strange that so independent a mind should be tolerated at all.\"<ref name=Spectator/> It argued in regards to the content about the [[invasion of Manchuria]] that it is \"a most valuable account\".<ref name=Spectator/>\n\nLanger praised the sourcing and described it as \"One of the most important books of the quarter.\"<ref name=Langer/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.6461 War And Diplomacy In The Japanese Empire]'' - [[Internet Archive]]\n* ''[https://www.questia.com/library/77350247/war-and-diplomacy-in-the-japanese-empire War and Diplomacy in the Japanese Empire]'' in [[Questia]]\n[[Category:1935 books]]\n{{book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WhisperToMe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_and_Diplomacy_in_the_Japanese_Empire"}
